# Public Prosecutor _v_ Haleem Bathusa Bin Abdul Rahim  

### \[2022\] SGMC 63

Criminal Law – Offences – Voluntarily Causing Hurt

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing – Principles

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9184/2022/01.\]

17 October 2022

### District Judge Chay Yuen Fatt:

## Introduction

1       The accused was a 46-year old male Singaporean involved in an incident of road rage. He was represented by counsel and he claimed trial to a charge of an offence under s 323 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) for voluntarily causing hurt to another driver on the road (the “victim”). The accused claimed that the victim was in fact the aggressor. The victim had passed away before the trial commenced. The victim’s death was unrelated to the offence.

2       At the conclusion of the trial, the accused’s defence was rejected and he was convicted of the single charge. He was sentenced to five weeks’ imprisonment. I had provided the parties with my brief reasons for the conviction and indicated that full grounds will be furnished if necessary. The accused has filed an appeal against both his conviction and sentence. The accused is on bail pending this appeal.

3       I now provide my full grounds for the conviction and sentence.

## The Charge

4       For ease of reference, I set out the single amended charge in full as follows:

> You… are charged that you, on 1 February 2020, shortly before 5.48am, near Hillview Community Club, did voluntarily cause hurt to one Gabriel Heng Jing Heng, to wit, by kicking, punching and hitting him, causing him to suffer left hand contusion, right eyelid contusion and nose contusion, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under section 323 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed).

5       The Prosecution made a minor amendment to the charge in that one of the stated injuries was amended from “right eye contusion” to “right eyelid contusion”. The amendment was made at the close of the Prosecution’s case following a clarification by the doctor who had examined the victim. The Defence did not raise any issue as to the amendment.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

## Prosecution’s Case

6       The Prosecution’s case and its evidence, where material and relevant, are summarised as follows.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

7       The offence was alleged to have occurred in the early morning of 1 February 2020 along Hillview Avenue (“the scene”), near Hillview Community Centre (“Hillview CC”). There were two eyewitnesses. One was a security officer on duty at the Hillview CC. The other was a taxi-driver who was driving along Hillview Avenue. The offence was also captured on CCTV installed at Hillview CC. The accused was alleged to have physically assaulted the victim causing the injuries to the victim as spelt out in the charge (the “incident” or “assault”).

8       Prior to the incident, both the accused and the victim were driving alone in their respective cars along the expressway on the morning in question. The Prosecution’s case was that around 5.00 am, the accused was involved in a disagreement with the victim regarding the manner in which the accused drove his car.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) He had swerved his car into the victim’s path and the victim sounded his horn and flashed his headlight at the accused.[^4] Both parties had a verbal exchange whilst still driving. The accused then exited the expressway and ended up stopping at the scene. The victim followed him and stopped his car behind the accused’s car. Both drivers alighted from their cars. The scene was near the accused’s residence[^5] at Hillview Rise.[^6]

9       At the scene, the accused physically assaulted the victim by hitting and kicking the victim causing injuries to the victim i.e. left hand contusion, right eyelid contusion, and nose contusion. The victim did not fight back. At some point, the victim showed a document to the accused telling the accused that he (the victim) had pending police cases.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7) That was the reason why the victim was restraining himself from fighting back.

#### Taxi-Driver’s Evidence

10     At about this time, a taxi arrived at the scene driven by the taxi-driver (PW2 Ang Beng Chye Ronnie). The taxi-driver stopped to see what was going on and spoke to the victim.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) The taxi-driver testified that he stopped because he saw and heard two men (the accused and the victim) arguing at the scene which was located just before the roundabout along Hillview Avenue.[^9] He differentiated the two parties as being of different race i.e. one was Chinese (the victim) and the other was an Indian man[^10] (the accused).[^11] The taxi-driver unequivocally identified the accused in court as the Indian man he saw that day.[^12] It was not in dispute that the taxi-driver was not asked by the investigating officer to identify the victim during the course of the investigations. However, as I will elaborate below, that is immaterial.

11     After assaulting the victim, the accused returned to his car and drove off i.e. he fled the scene.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) Both the taxi-driver and the victim tried to stop the accused from driving off. In frustration, the victim hit and kicked the accused’s car as the accused was driving away.[^14] The taxi-driver also tried to position his taxi to block the accused’s car but the accused managed to slip away.[^15]

12     The taxi-driver testified that “_the Chinese guy saw me and I was shocked to see him that his face was bleeding very heavily. And he did ask me to call the police, which I did_..”[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16) In contrast, the taxi-driver testified that the Indian man “looks perfect” and was not injured.[^17] The taxi-driver told the police that the Indian man had run off after beating someone.[^18] The taxi-driver testified that he could remember this case clearly because he had never encountered something like this in his 13 years driving a taxi.[^19]

13     The taxi-driver testified that the victim informed that he (the victim) had been beaten up by the Indian man. Even though he did not see the actual assault, the taxi-driver believed that it must be the case that the Indian man had beaten up the Chinese man because there was only two of them and they were arguing. It could not be that the Chinese man had inflicted the injuries on himself.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)

14     The victim requested the taxi-driver to call the police and provided the accused’s licence plate.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) The taxi-driver called ‘999’ with the information “The car SKH 7758B BMW beat somebody and ran away. The person is bleeding.” The text of this call reflecting the accused’s license plate number was admitted in evidence as the ‘first incident report’.[^22]

15     The police (PW4 SSSgt Mohamed Nasrudin bin Shahul Hameed) was activated at about 6 am and they visited the victim at his residence. The victim had returned home after the assault because his clothes were blood-stained. The police interviewed the victim. The victim informed that the other driver (referring to the accused) swerved his car left and right. The victim then signalled to him as to why he drove in that manner. They stopped to talk things out. The accused then started throwing punches at the victim. The accused also threw the victim’s mobile phone on the ground. When the victim was picking up the phone, the accused kicked him. The police recorded this interview on their portable “Cubicon 2” device at 7.12 am. The record of this verbal interview formed part of the entire first incident report with the event logs and was admitted in evidence.[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) The police also took a photos of the victim’s injured face and his blood-stained shirt.[^24]

16     The initial investigating officer (PW5 SI Hazmi bin Buang)(“initial IO”) identified and located the accused via the license plate number of the car that was provided to the police. It was not in dispute that the initial IO managed to track down the accused as the person who had rented the car bearing the said licence plate number.[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25)

#### Security officer’s evidence

17     As mentioned above, there was a security officer (PW6 Saiyed Javed Ahmad Farid Miya) on duty at Hillview CC who also witnessed the assault The assault was fortuitously captured on Hillview CC’s CCTV (“video footage” or “CCTV”). The video footage was extracted by the security officer.[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) The video footage captured what transpired near the entrance of the driveway to Hillview CC sometime after 5.00 am. The security officer testified that he heard a commotion and went to the window to see what was going on. He saw two men, one pushing the other who fell. The first man was beating the other man who was on the ground, and thereafter started kicking the fallen man.[^27] He described the man who was being beaten to be thinner and taller and wearing lighter coloured clothes.[^28]

18     The video footage was admitted in evidence without challenge[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29), except that the accused claimed that the faces of parties could not be clearly identified. The video footage was played in court multiple times to the witnesses, including the taxi-driver. The taxi-driver identified himself in the video footage[^30] and confirmed that he was the person present at the location.[^31]

#### Medical evidence

19     The victim was examined at Ng Teng Fong General Hospital after the assault on the same day. The victim provided a history of being assaulted. The doctor[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32) who examined the victim testified as to the injuries sustained by the victim. The injuries were a contusion on the left hand, a right eyelid contusion and nose contusion. The injuries were consistent with the history of an assault. The victim was prescribed painkillers and discharged with medical leave for 5 days.[^33]

#### Statements

20     The victim (Gabriel Heng) unfortunately passed away before the trial due to personal and unrelated circumstances. The death certificate proving his demise was admitted in evidence.[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34) He had provided a statement to the initial IO on 10 March 2020 before his passing. The said statement was admitted in evidence[^35] pursuant to s 32(1)(_j_)(i) of the Evidence Act as a statement made by a person who is dead. The Defence did not object to the admissibility of the statement. In his statement, the victim identified the license plate number of his assailant. The license plate number was traced to the accused’s rented car. There was no dispute that the accused had rented the car on a long- term basis and was in fact driving the said car that night.

21     The accused likewise gave a statement to the initial IO on 19 February 2020 recorded under s 22 of the Criminal Procedure Code. The statement was admitted in evidence as agreed by the Defence.[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36) The Prosecution pointed out that the accused admitted in his statement to punching the victim twice.[^37]

## Close of Prosecution’s Case

22     At the close of the Prosecution’s case, the Defence submitted that there was no case for the accused to answer simply because the identity of the assailant was disputed and which was not proved by any of the witnesses.

23     However, I agreed with the Prosecution that there was certainly prima facie evidence to link the accused to the assault and to identify the accused to be assailant. At the very least, there was, before the court, the victim’s statement, the testimonies of the security officer and the taxi-driver, and the video footage capturing the entire incident. I therefore called on the accused to give his defence.

## The Defence

24     The accused elected to give evidence. He was the only defence witness. His defence is summarised in the Defence’s closing submission as follows.

25     The accused denied assaulting the victim. The Defence submitted that the victim was not available (for obvious reason) to testify in court and to identify the accused as the assailant.[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38)

26     The Defence stressed that the victim was not even asked by the police to identify the accused during the investigations before the victim passed away.[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39) Neither the taxi-driver nor the security officer were asked to identify the accused during the investigations. None of the Prosecution’s witnesses at the scene (including the police) could identify the accused as the assailant.[^40] In fact, of the two eye-witnesses, the security officer was not able to recognise the accused in the dock.[^41]

27     The accused claimed that right from the start, the victim was the aggressive party having followed him to the scene after getting into each other’s way when driving.[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42) The accused denied assaulting the victim and blamed the victim for being aggressive. The accused merely acted in self-defence.[^43] The accused testified that he was the real ‘victim’ of an unprovoked and vicious assault by the other driver,[^44] and that he was hit and kicked even after falling to the ground. He did not retaliate but only fended off the blows.[^45] The accused also claimed that he did not see any blood on the other person’s face.[^46] On the other hand, he suffered injuries to his chest, face and hand as a result of the attack on him.[^47]

28     As regards the video footage, the Defence submitted that the accused’s face could not be clearly seen on the video footage and it also cannot be seen who was hitting whom.[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) In the alternative, the Defence submitted that the accused was at most guilty of the lesser offence under s 358 of the Penal Code for using criminal force on the victim on grave and sudden provocation.[^49]

29     I noted that the Defence’s submissions did not go so far as to say that the accused was not one of the two persons captured on the CCTV, never mind who was the aggressor. There was certainly no defence of alibi. Nonetheless, I also noted that when the accused gave his evidence, he did say that it was not clear if he was one of the two persons captured in the video footage. The accused said he “totally disagree\[d\]”[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50) with the CCTV footage because it was unclear.[^51] Implicit in those remarks was perhaps an allusion to the possibility that he was not present or involved at all in the incident.

## Verdict

30     The accused was found guilty and was convicted of the charge at the conclusion of the trial.

## Reasons for Conviction

31     Notwithstanding that the victim did not testify in court due his demise, I was satisfied that there was more than sufficient and cogent evidence to prove the charge against the accused beyond reasonable doubt.

#### Undisputed and indisputable facts

32     I agree with the Prosecution’s submission that it cannot be gainsaid that the video footage (P7) fully recorded the assault from start to end.[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52) The video footage captured the events from the time the two cars pulled up to scene (i.e. the kerb outside Hillview CC) until the time when the car in front drove off. It was not in dispute that one car had followed the other car[^53]and both cars then stopped one (“first car”) in front of the other (“second car”). It was also not disputed that the scene was located opposite the accused’s residence.[^54]

33     The drivers of the two cars alighted. I will refer to them as the first driver (coming out of the first car) and the second driver (alighting from the second car) respectively. There was an altercation between the two drivers prior to the assault. It was clearly seen and I found that the altercation and the assault involved only the two drivers and no one else. There were no passengers in the two cars.

34     After the assault, a third person arrived at the scene. It was not in dispute that the third person was the taxi-driver. The taxi-driver in fact identified his taxi pulling up[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) and being flagged down by one of the drivers who then spoke to the taxi-driver.[^56]

#### Two questions

35     The case essentially turned on two key questions which were:

> (a)     Was the accused one of the two drivers captured in the video footage, and if so;

> (b)     Was he the assailant or the ‘victim’.

I will address and answer these two questions in turn.

#### (a)   Was the accused one of the two drivers captured in the video footage?

36     I was satisfied beyond reasonable doubt and I found that the accused was one of the drivers captured in the footage.

37     First and foremost, there was no doubt that the victim was one of the drivers. He was the person whom the taxi-driver had assisted at the scene to call the police. The victim’s identity was established by the police who visited and interviewed him at his residence about two hours after the incident.

38     As for the identity of the other driver, the taxi-driver positively identified the accused in court to be the ‘Indian man’ who was the other driver and who had driven off as shown in the CCTV footage. I believed the evidence of the taxi-driver who had provided a clear and consistent account of what happened after his taxi had arrived at the scene. I accepted his evidence that the Chinese man (established to be the victim) had requested him to call the police,[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) and that he tried to position his taxi to block the other driver from driving off,[^58]but that the Indian man managed to slip away in his car,[^59] and also that the Chinese man then provided the license plate number of the Indian man’s car for him to call the police.[^60] His account of events were consistent with and borne out by the video footage. I also considered that the taxi-driver was able to recall the events clearly, no doubt with the benefit of refreshing his memory from watching the video footage in court, but also because he said he had never encountered such a situation in the 13 years of being a taxi-driver. I found that he was an independent and truthful witness and I saw no reason to doubt the veracity and accuracy of his testimony.

39     Quite apart from the taxi-driver’s identification of the accused, the license plate number as provided by the victim to the taxi-driver was traced to the car that was rented by the accused. The model of the accused’s rental car matched that of the car as shown in the video footage and as described by the taxi-driver. That could not have simply been a coincidence.

40     In any event, the accused admitted that he had a run-in on the road with another driver who then followed him to somewhere near his residence. He was driving the exact same car SKH 7758B. There was an altercation which turned physical. He admitted in his statement that he punched the other driver twice but explained in court that he was only trying to fend off the other driver. He insisted that the other driver was the aggressor. He then drove off even as the other driver hit and kicked his car. He did not make a police report regarding his encounter with the other driver.

41     It was clear to me that by his own admission, the accused was describing the very same incident as captured in the video footage. There was no evidence of another similar incident at or around the material location and time in question. The accused also did not make a police report of another such incident. The accused did not adduce any evidence of alibi. Even though the accused was reluctant to equivocally acknowledge that he was one of the drivers captured in the video footage, there was no question and I found that he was indeed one of the said drivers in the said video footage capturing the assault. In other words, he was not involved in some other similar or concurrent incident.

42     I also noted that the closing submission filed by the accused’s counsel was premised on the defence that the accused was one of the drivers in the incident in question except that the Defence blamed the victim as the aggressor. This premise is clear from the relevant portions under the sub-heading “Defence” starting from \[10\] of counsel’s written submission as follows:

> It is submitted that in the 1 February 2020 incident, Gabriel Heng \[_the deceased victim_\] was the aggressor. After the Accused accidentally swerved into his lane, Gabriel chased behind the Accuse in his car and got out of his car to confront the Accused. Gabriel Heng had walked towards the Accused with something shiny in his hand and tried to attack the Accused. The Accused acted in self defence to protect himself from Gabriel Heng.[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61)

> According to the Accused, it was Gabriel Heng who was the aggressor. The Accused had swerved his car onto Gabriel Heng’s path and angered Gabriel Heng. Gabriel Heng started scolding the Accused with vulgar words, gesturing at him, pressing the car horn and using his car’s high beam on the Accused. Gabriel Heng then chased after the Accused’s car.[^62]

> ..the CCTV footage supports the Accused’s testimony that it was Gabriel who refused to let the Accused go and chased after him in his car until the Accused stopped by the road because the accused did not want Gabriel to find out where he lived exactly.[^63]

> The Accused explained that the reason why he left after PW2 Ronnie Ang \[_the taxi-driver_\] came was because he heard Gabriel Heng and PW2 Ronnie Ang speaking in Chinese and the Accused was worried that the two Chinese men might gang up against him.[^64]

43     As may be seen from counsel’s submission, the Defence accepted that the accused did encounter the victim, Gabriel Heng, that early morning.

44     In fact, counsel referred to and confirmed the act of the victim at the scene when the victim showed the accused a document (relating to the victim’s pending court case) as follows:

> Gabriel Heng’s reason for showing the Accused his paper from Invictus Law Corporation makes no sense. If Gabriel Heng was really the victim, then there was completely no need for him to justify himself to the accused. If Gabriel Heng had done nothing wrong, there would be no need for Gabriel Heng to specially retrieve his paper from Invictus Law Corporation and show it to the Accused.[\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65)

45     This act was mentioned in both the accused’s statement and the victim’s statement as acknowledged by counsel in his submission.[\[note: 66\]](#Ftn_66) In fact, the accused even provided more details of the said document than was revealed in the victim’s statement. This common reference to the same act (and with added details provided by the accused) inexorably linked the accused to the encounter with the victim and tied him to the incident.

46     In any event, the accused had described, in both his statement[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67) and oral evidence, an encounter and a physical altercation with another driver on the road that was remarkably similar to the incident captured on the CCTV footage. Short of admitting outright and conceding that he was one of the drivers shown in the footage, the accused was most certainly describing and referring to the same incident.

47     For the above reasons, there was absolutely no doubt that the first question must be answered in the affirmative i.e. the accused was one of the two drivers at the scene as captured in the video footage.

#### (b)   Was the accused the assailant or the ‘victim’?

48     Now that it has been established that the two drivers in video footage were the accused and the victim, the follow-on question was whether the accused was the assailant in the footage and as charged or rather the ‘victim” as he claimed in his defence.

49     It may be that the faces of the two drivers were unrecognisable on the video footage because of the distance from which the video footage was captured of the incident. However, the two drivers can easily be distinguished by other identifiers (apart from their faces) all of which were clearly seen on the CCTV. We could quite easily tell the two drivers apart from their body shape, the colour of their clothes and their respective actions. Thus, the security officer was able to distinguish the two drivers when he described the victim who was being beaten to be thinner and taller and wearing lighter coloured clothes.[\[note: 68\]](#Ftn_68) In this regard, I noted in court that the accused has a relatively short and stocky body shape.

50     Further, the first car was driven by the accused and the driver who was seen alighting from the first car would be the accused. Consequently, the second car (pulling up and parking behind the accused’s car) was driven by the victim and the person seen alighting from the second car would be the victim. The different and clearly distinguishable actions of the two drivers thereafter were clearly captured and may be attributed to the accused and the victim respectively.

51     As regards their respective actions, the Prosecution has accurately highlighted the material parts of the CCTV footage that captured the accused assaulting the victim. The sequence of events is stated as follows:[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69)

> (a)     At 08:37 to 08:39 (timestamp 06:08:35 to 06:08:37), the accused punches the victim twice as the latter leans against the windshield of the second car.

> (b)     At 08:41 to 08:43 (timestamp 06:08:38 to 06:08:41), the victim falls to the road, on his back, and the accused gets on top of him in a kneeling position.

> (c)     At 08:47 to 08:49 (timestamp 06:08:44 to 06:08:46), the accused hits the victim thrice while the victim is lying on the road.

> (d)     At 08:52 to 08:53 (timestamp 06:08:50 to 06:08:51), the accused kicks the victim once while the victim is still lying on the road.

> (e)     At 08:56 to 09:00 (timestamp 06:08:53 to 06:08:58), the victim gets up and backs away. He appears to be a little dazed.

> (f)     At 09:02 to 09:03 (timestamp 06:09:00 to 06:09:01), the accused hits the victim with his left hand, causing the victim to lose his balance and sit on the ground.

> (g)     At 09:04 to 09:07 (timestamp 06:09:02 to 06:09:05), the victim gets up and runs away as the accused attempts to kick him. As the victim approaches the CCTV, it appears that he is of a taller and thinner build than the accused and is wearing a long-sleeved light-coloured shirt, as seen in these screenshots from P7 at 09:08 (timestamp 06:09:05), in which the accused is on the left and the victim is on the right:

![](data:image;base64,)

![](data:image;base64,)

> (h)     At 09:09 to 09:10 (timestamp 06:09:07 to 06:09:08), the accused attempts to elbow the victim’s head as he turned away to shield his head and kicks the back of the victim’s leg once.

52     The footage continues to capture the accused returning to the first car and driving off,[\[note: 70\]](#Ftn_70) and the victim is seen hitting and kicking the escaping car.[^71]

53     If we bookend the entire incident of assault with the accused alighting from the first car in the beginning and him driving away at the end, we could clearly track his actions of pushing, punching and kicking the victim. It would also be clearly seen that the assault by the accused was entirely one-sided and that the victim did not retaliate at all.

54     There was no doubt that the victim was the driver who was being assaulted and that the assailant was indubitably the accused. Therefore, it is immaterial that the drivers’ faces could not be identified from the video footage. Their identities were readily and reliably established on the video footage through other identifying features.

55     I also disregarded as unmeritorious the Defence’s submission that the witnesses were not asked to identify the victim or the accused during the investigations, or that the victim was not asked to identify the accused before the victim passed away. Following my above analysis of the available evidence which irrefutably established that the accused was the first driver who had assaulted the victim, it is immaterial that no identification was carried out during investigations as challenged by the Defence. Even then, as regards face-to-fact identification, the security officer did in fact identify the accused in court (both with and without his face mask) as the other driver who had driven off from the scene. I reiterate that I accepted the taxi-driver’s evidence as reliable and truthful.

#### Evidence apart from video footage

56     Apart from the video footage, there were other evidence to prove that the accused was the assailant who had assaulted the victim.

57     First, the victim was injured following the incident as evidenced by the two photographs which the police had taken contemporaneously of the victim.[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72) One photo showed a blood-stained long-sleeved white top that the victim was wearing during the incident (as seen on the video footage)[^73] and the other photo showed the victim’s bloodied face.[^74]

58     Second, the security officer clearly identified, without the need for facial identification, who was hitting whom. As already stated above, the security officer testified that the person being assaulted fell after he was pushed, and was then beaten and kicked as he lay on the floor.[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75) The security officer identified the victim to be taller and thinner than the assailant and wearing a lighter shade of clothing.[^76] It was plainly seen from the screen grab extracted by the Prosecution from the footage[^77] that the victim, standing next to the accused, was indeed taller and slimmer and also wearing a much lighter top. The security officer’s account was also consistent with the portion of the video footage showing the accused hitting and kicking the victim who was lying helplessly on the ground.[^78]

59     Third, the taxi-driver testified that the victim was bleeding profusely on the face.[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79) In stark contrast, he testified that the accused did not suffer a single scratch. He described that the accused looked “_perfect, there is no injury on him_”.[^80] The taxi-driver’s description was consistent with what was shown on the footage that the assault was one-sided. It was also consistent with the accused’s evidence that he did not seek medical attention despite claiming to have suffered injuries.[^81]

60     Finally, I considered that the accused admitted in his own statement that he had punched the victim twice in the face. The accused also stated that he saw that there was blood on the victim’s face.[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82) I agreed with Prosecution’s submission that his admission lined up clearly with the two punches thrown by the assailant as seen on the video footage.[^83] I also agreed that it was very telling that the accused did not allege in his statement that the victim had assaulted him. This was a glaring omission which undermined his Defence at trial.

61     For the foregoing reasons and in conclusion, the answer to the second key question was and must be that the accused was the assailant who had assaulted the victim as alleged in the charge. He tried to play the ‘victim’ but unfortunately, that role did not sit well with all the objective evidence. I will elaborate on this further below.

#### Victim’s statement

62     I found that the victim’s statement was faithfully, accurately and contemporaneously recorded by the initial IO on 10 March 2020. I agree with Prosecution’s submission that the victim’s account of the incident was internally consistent and was externally consistent with the video footage of the incident.

63     The Prosecution has correctly correlated the victim’s statement with the relevant portions of the video footage as follows:[\[note: 84\]](#Ftn_84)

64     As rightly pointed out by the Prosecution, the victim did not have the opportunity to view the footage prior to giving his statement to the police.[\[note: 85\]](#Ftn_85) I agreed that the victim would not have been able to dovetail his statement with the video footage. I found that the video footage independently and materially validated the victim’s statement. The victim was therefore objectively recounting an incident (which happened to be captured by the CCTV) between the accused and him. He was not referring to any other random and strangely similar incident with another unknown person which had occurred by coincidence at the same location and time.

65     I rejected the Defence’s submission that the victim’s statement was “not tested through cross-examination” and was therefore prejudicial to the accused.[\[note: 86\]](#Ftn_86) The Defence had agreed to the admission of the victim’s statement under s 32(1)(j)(i) of the Evidence Act because the victim was dead. It is a pre-condition under the said statutory provision that the witness must be dead for the witness’s statement to be admitted. It is a given that such statement would not be tested by way of cross-examination of the witness. In the present case, there was no dispute that the victim was dead. His statement cannot be considered as “prejudicial” by reason of the inevitable consequence (that the witness would not be present for cross-examination) of the very pre-condition of its admissibility. Therefore, it does not lie in the Defence’s mouth to describe the victim’s statement as prejudicial simply because counsel cannot cross-examine the victim. Counsel has not cited any other reason to disparage the statement as being prejudicial. I did not find any grounds to render the statement prejudicial to the accused or his Defence. There was no necessity or reason to exercise my discretion to exclude the victim’s statement.

66     As correctly acknowledged by counsel in his submission at the close of the Prosecution’s case, when the statement is admitted (as in the present case), s 32(5) of the Evidence Act provides that it is then for the court to assign such weight to the statement as the court deems fit. I was of the view that the victim’s statement was entirely reliable in the material aspects of the case and the charge. In particular, the victim recounted that the accused initially took something from the boot of his car wanting to hit the victim but changed his mind. The victim also recounted that the accused pushed the victim onto the windscreen area of the victim’s car and started punching the victim. The victim also recounted that he fell onto the ground and the accused then kicked the victim in the face and head area. The victim’s account was entirely consistent with and borne out by the objective video footage evidence.

#### Victim’s pending matters largely irrelevant

67     I rejected Defence’s submission that the victim’s statement was unreliable because the victim’s pending criminal cases gave the victim an incentive to lie and to incriminate the accused and to cover up the victim’s assault of the accused.[\[note: 87\]](#Ftn_87) With respect, Counsel’s submission was not very well thought through and made no sense whatsoever. In essence, it was nothing more than a below the belt attempt (presumably on the instructions of the accused) to harp on the victim’s pending criminal matters[^88] which was calculated to smear the victim’s character. The Defence was no doubt trying to paint the victim as the crook with a motive to lie, and to portray the accused as the saint who was persuaded and prepared to let the victim off.[^89] The victim’s pending criminal matters were a red herring and largely irrelevant except to explain why the victim did not retaliate against the accused when he could easily have done so.

68     I agreed with the Prosecution’s submission[\[note: 90\]](#Ftn_90) that these were spurious allegations which conveniently glossed over the fact the victim had requested the taxi-driver to call the police and the police was in fact summoned.[^91] The Defence’s submission defied logic and common sense because if the victim had wanted to stay out of trouble (allegedly because of his pending criminal matters), he would not have attacked the accused, then persuade the accused not to report him and then promptly call the police on himself. Therefore, I found that the victim has no reason to lie about an incident which he had himself reported to the police against his own interest.

69     On the contrary, as rightly pointed out by the Prosecution, the victim was so honest and truthful that he even told the police that he hit and kicked the accused’s car[\[note: 92\]](#Ftn_92) which acts subsequently formed the subject of a charge of mischief against him.[^93] The victim owned up to his acts of mischief even though he would not have known about the CCTV footage when he gave his statement to the police. The victim’s willingness to incriminate himself, not having watched the video footage, bore testament to his truthfulness and honesty when he provided his statement. On the contrary, the same cannot be said of the accused. Even when confronted with the video footage multiple times, the accused would not admit his wrongdoing. To add insult to injury, he even ‘pretended’ to be the victim, a point which I will return to later.

#### Inconsistencies in victim’s statement immaterial

70     I also rejected the Defence’s submission that the victim lied about his injuries in the statement because he did not inform the doctor or the police officer who first visited him that he was semiconscious or that he was choked by the accused.[\[note: 94\]](#Ftn_94) I would not overstate these apparent inconsistences. I agreed with Prosecution’s submission that in assessing a witness’s evidence (or statement), the context in which any discrepancy arose is critical.[^95] Particularly in the context of inconsistencies or omissions within a first information report (“FIR”), See J held in _Koh Jing Kwang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 1 SLR 7</span> at \[27\] that the court could take into account the circumstances in which the FIR was made.

71     In the present case, I considered that the victim’s initial oral account to the police that morning (which was essentially the FIR provided by the said victim) had taken place very shortly after the offence. In fact, he had just returned home after being assaulted by the accused and his face was still bloodied as evidenced by the contemporaneous photos taken of him. He also informed the police that he was having a headache and not in the best state of mind to be interviewed.[\[note: 96\]](#Ftn_96) Given those circumstances including the physical condition and state of mind of the victim, he may have unintentionally omitted one or two details. Such omissions do not necessarily affect the credibility of a witness. Thus, See J held in _Low Song Chye v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGHC 140</span> (“_Low Song Chye_”) at \[35\] that the fact that the victim in that case had not referred to the grabbing of her neck in any of the medical reports or in the FIR, was not such a material discrepancy that would affect her credibility.

72     Similarly, I took the view that the discrepancies highlighted by the Defence in the present case were immaterial and were entirely understandable and explicable. I found that the discrepancies did not materially undermine the reliability of the victim’s statement which was recorded more than a month later when the victim would have recovered from the traumatic and injurious assault. In any event, the history provided to the doctor and the oral account provided to the police on the morning of the offence were fundamentally and largely consistent with the victim’s subsequent statement.

#### With or without statement

73     For the foregoing reasons, I accorded full weight to the victim’s statement. He victim may have been aggressive (initially in following the accused to the scene and verbally confronting the accused, and at the end when he chased after the accused’s car to stop the accused from fleeing the scene) but it was the accused who had physically attacked the victim. As such, the accused was the aggressor and not the innocent and meek person that he would like the court to believe.

74     I will add that even without reference to or reliance on the victim’s statement, there was more than ample and cogent evidence to establish beyond reasonable doubt that the accused was the driver in the first car and that he had physically assaulting the victim causing the latter bodily injuries. In other words, even without the victim’s statement, the rest of the Prosecution’s evidence would have been adequate to prove the charge against the accused beyond reasonable doubt.

## Defence Rejected

#### Accused was cunning and opportunistic

75     I disbelieved the accused’s testimony and rejected his defence that he was the actual ‘victim’. He was certainly a most devious and calculative individual having first slipped away from the scene of the offence, and now denying his involvement in the incident by opportunistically taking full advantage of the victim’s death and consequent absence from court, in the hope that he would not be identified. He also capitalised on the victim’s absence by blaming and disparaging the victim saying the victim was the aggressive party in tailing and confronting him. However, by the accused’s own admission in his statement, the accused was driving badly swerving into the path of the victim. In light of the accused’s reckless driving, the victim would have good reason to be aggrieved and to want to confront the accused.

76     Even if the victim was initially aggressive in following the accused’s car to the scene and wanting to confront the accused, I was satisfied that it was the accused who first laid hands on the victim. He was even going to arm himself with some form of weapon from the boot of his car to confront the victim but changed his mind. I was also satisfied that the victim refrained himself from fighting back because the victim was already facing unrelated criminal proceedings and did not want to get into more trouble with the law. The victim made his position and personal circumstance known to the accused, by showing the accused a document relating to victim’s criminal proceedings. Consistent with his opportunistic nature, the accused took advantage of the victim’s restraint to further assault the victim. The accused then brought up the victim’s pending criminal matter in his defence in court to disparage the victim’s character and to impute bad faith on the victim.

77     Considering all the circumstances, I was convinced and found that the accused had assaulted the victim and not the other way round.

#### Accused was evasive and unremorseful

78     I found the accused to be an extremely evasive and slippery witness. This is clearly illustrated by the fact that despite all the evidence staring him in the face, including the video footage, he was reluctant to acknowledge that he was in fact one of the drivers captured in the video footage. His lack of remorse was simply astounding.

#### Accused shamelessly playing victim

79     As already set out above, the accused shamelessly claimed that he was the ‘victim’ of an unprovoked vicious assault by the other driver,[\[note: 97\]](#Ftn_97) and that he was hit and kicked even after falling to the ground. Without batting an eyelid, he claimed that he did not retaliate and but only fended off the blows.[^98] He also claimed that he did not see any blood on the other person’s face.[^99] Quite incredibly, he claimed he suffered injuries to his chest, face and hand.[^100]

80     I could see what the accused tried to do in court and in his defence. He was banking on the fact that the faces in the video footage could not be recognised and he was trying to trick the court into believing that he was the other driver in the footage i.e. Gabriel Heng. In effect, he was pretending that he was Gabriel Heng in the footage and trying to play the victim in more ways than one. Unfortunately, his ruse, sly as it was, failed because he was not the taller and slimmer person, nor was he wearing lighter coloured clothing. More importantly, he was not injured unlike the true victim, Gabriel Heng.

#### Defence inconsistent with accused’s statement

81     The accused’s defence at trial was also materially inconsistent with his statement. He told the police in his statement that he punched the other driver twice in the face and he also noticed some blood on that person’s face. In his oral evidence however, he claimed he did not hit the other party and also that he did not see any blood on the other party. He also claimed to have suffered injuries to his left forearm, a scratch on the back of his neck and swelling on his right toes.[\[note: 101\]](#Ftn_101) This revelation was absent in his statement. In my view, he could not explain the inconsistencies under cross-examination. These were material and glaring inconsistencies giving rise to diametrically opposed defences. I agreed with the Prosecution and found that the accused lied in his oral testimony.

#### Defence inconsistent with objective circumstances

82     I considered that the accused’s defence that he was the real ‘victim’ to be inconsistent with the fact that (i) he fled the scene, (ii) he did not lodge a police report against the victim, and (iii) no evidence was tendered by the Defence to show that the accused suffered any injury. I dismissed his explanation for not reporting the victim to the police i.e. that he did not want to get the victim into trouble. His explanation beggared belief. If he had felt threatened by the victim whom he described to have aggressively followed him to the vicinity of his home, he would have called the police on the victim. The accused was not at all the kind and forgiving man as he would like the court to believe.

83     Rather, the circumstances were in fact the reverse i.e. the taxi-driver tried to stop the accused from fleeing, the victim requested the taxi-driver to call the police for assistance, and the victim had suffered multiple injuries as evidenced by the doctor and the contemporaneous photo of the victim. These object circumstances very much comport with the narrative that it was a one-sided assault by the accused on the victim.

#### Alternative defences or charges rejected

84     I rejected the Defence’s suggestion that the injuries suffered by the victim may have been due to a fall. Considering the totality of the evidence and for the above reasons, I ruled out that suggestion as nothing more than a desperate and half-hearted grasping of a thin straw of an illusory defence.

85     I further rejected the Defence’s submission for alternative charges on the basis that the accused had acted in self-defence or that he had, at most, used criminal force against the victim on grave and sudden provocation.[\[note: 102\]](#Ftn_102) I found that there was no provocation on the part of the victim. In any event, these suggested alternative charges were incongruous with the accused’s defence at trial that he was the ‘victim’ and that he did not hit, punch or kick the victim at any time.[^103] I thoroughly rejected the suggested alternative scenarios in light my clear findings above.

## Conclusion

86     I believed the testimony of the taxi-driver who identified (i) the accused as the driver who fled the scene, and (ii) the victim as the injured party. I also believed the evidence of the security officer who identified the victim as the taller, slimmer person wearing lighter colour clothes. Based on the video footage, it was established that it was the accused who had physically assaulted the victim (Gabriel Heng) and had caused him bodily injuries. The victim did not retaliate. The finding that the accused was the assailant was consistent with the surrounding objective circumstances. It was immaterial that the witnesses were not asked during investigations to identify the victim or the accused, or that that victim was not asked to identify the accused before his passing.

87     The victim’s statement was also consistent with the video footage and proved that it was the accused who had assaulted the victim and not the other way round. I was satisfied that the victim chose not to and did not in fact retaliate against the accused. I found that the victim’s then pending criminal charges were irrelevant to the victim’s credibility or the weight to be assigned to his statement. They were only relevant to explain why the victim did not retaliate even when he was assaulted and injured by the accused.

88     I disbelieved the accused whom I assessed to be conniving, deceitful and opportunistic. His claim to be the ‘victim’ was as shameless as it was incredible. I found that the accused was the aggressor and had physically attacked the victim without provocation. I found that the accused caused the injuries as stated in the charge. He was not the ‘victim’ even though he pretended to be one. I further found that he lied in his oral evidence. In short, I rejected the accused’s defence that he was assaulted by the victim, Gabriel Heng. Nothing could be further from the truth.

89     Having carefully considered all the evidence, I found that the prosecution has proved the charge against the accused beyond reasonable doubt. Accordingly, the accused was convicted of the charge.

## Sentence

90     The Prosecution sought a sentence of 5 to 6 weeks’ imprisonment.[\[note: 104\]](#Ftn_104) I should quickly point out that in Prosecution’s written submission on sentence, it is stated at the top that the Prosecution was seeking a sentencing of “_9 to 12 weeks’ imprisonment, fine of at least $10,000 and 24 months’ DQAC_.” Less there should be any confusion at the appeal, I should explain that this was Prosecution’s proposed _global sentence_ on the premise that the accused was going to plead guilty to his other stood-down traffic-related offences after he was convicted of the present charge. However, any question of a global sentence became moot when the accused indicated that he would be contesting those other charges. In any event, I had clarified with the parties that the Prosecution was indeed seeking a sentence of 5 to 6 six week’s imprisonment for the present charge.[^105]

91     As for the Defence, counsel for the accused filed a written mitigation plea on behalf of the accused.[\[note: 106\]](#Ftn_106) Counsel asked for only a fine plus one day’s imprisonment to be imposed, or alternatively, a two-week jail sentence.[^107]

#### Prosecution’s sentencing submission

92     I preferred and accepted the Prosecution’s sentencing position which was more appropriate, albeit charitable. The Prosecution referred to and relied on the sentencing framework laid down in _Low Song Chye_ (“_Low Song Chye framework_”). As the maximum prescribed imprisonment sentence for an offence under s 323 of the Penal Code was increased on 1 January 2020 from two years to three years, I agreed with Prosecution’s proposal that the sentencing bands within the _Low Song Chye_ framework should be increased correspondingly by a factor of 1.5 times. Therefore, the upper end of the indicative imprisonment range for Band 1 would be extrapolated from four weeks to six weeks.

93     The Prosecution highlighted several aggravating factors. I agreed that these factors were relevant. First, it was submitted that the present case was an incident of road rage. The Defence did not disagree with this submission. Being an incident of road rage, I was of the view that the starting sentence (within Band 1 of the extrapolated _Low Song Chai_ framework) would be a custodial sentence and not simply a fine or even a token jail sentence. In the absence of exceptional circumstances, counsel’s submission for a fine and a one-day imprisonment sentence was grossly inadequate and misconceived.

94     The Prosecution highlighted a second aggravating factor which was that the accused had attacked the victim’s face. This was undeniably a vulnerable part of the human body. The evidence that the victim bled profusely on the face showed that the injury to his face was not insignificant.

95     The Prosecution highlighted a third aggravating factor in that the assault was persistent. The accused hit and kicked the victim even after the victim had fallen onto the ground. He continued to assault the victim even though the victim was trying to disengage from him.

The Prosecution added that the accused was convicted after trial and therefore, was not entitled to any sentencing discount. In conclusion, the Prosecution submitted that the accused ought to be sentenced to 5 to 6 weeks’ imprisonment within Band 1 of the revised _Low Song Chye_ framework.

#### Defence’s sentencing submission

96     I rejected counsel’s alternative submission for only a 2-week imprisonment sentence. I considered the precedents involving cases of road rage tendered by both the Prosecution and the Defence. These were all reported decisions. The accused persons in these precedents were all sentenced to at least four weeks’ imprisonment for a similar charge under s 323 of the Penal Code, even when the offender had pleaded guilty to the charge.[\[note: 108\]](#Ftn_108) The single precedent in _Public Prosecutor v Oon Joo Seng_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGMC 23</span> (“_Oon Joo Seng_”) which counsel cited also showed that the accused had received a sentence of 4 weeks’ imprisonment. I did not agree with counsel that the facts in _Oon Joo Seng_ were more egregious than the present case and that the present accused should therefore receive a lower imprisonment sentence. On the contrary, I was of the view that the assault in the present case was merciless and longer in duration, and the consequent injuries were more serious than _Oon Joo Seng_. By counsel’s own calculation, the attack in the present case lasted 43 seconds long.[^109] I considered that this was a fairly long duration by any reasonable and objective standard.

97     I also disagreed that the accused ought to receive a lower sentence (compared to _Oon Joo Seng_) because it was the victim who first confronted the accused. I took the view that unless it amounted to provocation (which was not my finding), it did not and should not matter who confronted whom or whose manner of driving was at fault. Given the limited road space and large number of cars on our roads, there will invariably be disagreement and even arguments amongst drivers on the road. However, such disagreement must never be allowed to escalate into violence, regardless of who was driving correctly or who had started the argument. That is the fundamental thinking and policy underpinning the principle of general deterrence when sentencing offenders in road rage cases. We must never allow ouselves to be consumed by rage and commit violence against other road users. This sentencing policy cannot therefore be applied with any less severity against the accused, as suggested by counsel, simply because it was the victim who had initally confronted the accused. Simply put, the accused crossed the line when he physically attacked the victim.

#### Public Prosector v Shi Ka Yee

98     I also cited to counsel, as a sentencing precedent, my decision in _Public Prosecutor v Shi Ka Yee_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] SGMC 21</span> (“_Shi Ka Yi_”). That was a highly publicised case of road rage where the accused was a 72 year-old elderly woman whom the media called the ‘Ferrari Lady’ because she was driving a Ferrari. In that case, she claimed that the victim’s parked car was blocking her passage. A verbal argument ensued and she slapped the victim once on his cheek causing a minor scratch. She was convicted after trial and sentenced to six weeks’ imprisonment. Her sentence was upheld on appeal.[^110]

99     In my written grounds of decision for _Shi Ka Yi_, I traced the jurisprudential history of when the High Court first held that the primary sentencing consideration in road rage cases is that of general and specific deterrence, and that a custodial sentence is warranted to properly and effectively give effect to the principle of deterrence. It is not necessary for me to set out those grounds in _Shi Ka Yi_ here.

100    Suffice to say that in _Shi Ka Yi_, I had similarly found the accused to be the aggressor who had similarly cast spurious accusations against the victim. I also found no compelling or extenuating circumstances to impose a lower sentence, notwithstanding that she was an elderly person and a first offender. She was also suffering from depression, albeit not a condition which materially contributed to her commission of the offence. The accused’s assault in _Shi Ka Yi_ was only a single slap. The assault was certainly far less egregious than the present case. If anything, the present accused deserved a higher sentence.

101    At this point, I must point out that I had remembered the sentence I imposed in _Shi Ka Yee_ to be four weeks’ imprisonment when the sentence was in fact six weeks’ imprisonment.[\[note: 111\]](#Ftn_111) The sentence of six weeks’ imprisonment was ultimately affirmed on appeal. In comparison, the assault in the present case was certainly more egregious than _Shi Ka Yi_. Therefore, had I remembered the sentence correctly, I would have sentenced the present accused to six weeks’ imprisonment i.e. at the upper limit of the Prosecution’s sentencing position. I would not have sentenced the accused any higher than six weeks’ imprisonment (even though justified) because the Prosecution did not submit for a sentence higher than six weeks’ imprisonment.

102    I did not make an order of compensation (as was done in _Shi Ka Yee_) since the victim in this case has passed away and the Prosecution also did not seek a compensation order.

#### Personal circumstance not mitigatory

103    Turning back to counsel’s mitigation plea, I did not find any compelling feature to justify a sentence shorter than that submitted by the Prosecution. The accused’s personal circumstances as informed in counsel’s mitigation were entirely unexceptional and do not attenuate the accused’s culpability at all to justify a markedly lower sentence.

#### Loss of employment not a mitigating factor

104    I also did not accord any weight to the counsel’s plea that the accused might lose his license as a property agent as a result of his conviction.[\[note: 112\]](#Ftn_112) This was not a valid mitigating factor. The possibility that the accused might lose his job would be considered an “extrinsic factor” which Sundaresh Menon CJ decided in _M Raveendran v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 254</span> to be difficult for the court to assess and therefore cannot be considered for purposes of sentence. Menon CJ explained at \[32\]-\[34\] why downstream consequences cannot be considered by the sentencing court:

> …extrinsic factors are _downstream consequences_ that might or would befall the offender because of the imposition of a sentence. If the courts were to take such consequences into account, there would be no logical limits as to when or how these consequences should be factored into sentencing. In my judgment, these consequences cannot meaningfully be considered in this context for at least three reasons. First, it is impossible for the court to place a value on such downstream consequences and to translate the potential financial losses into an appropriate reduction in sentence. The two are simply incommensurable.

> Second, the different potential financial losses that could be faced by offenders cannot meaningfully be compared, given the varied consequences that one could suffer flowing from a particular sentence. Some might face these consequences upon any conviction; while others only upon the imposition of any term of imprisonment or one of a certain length. Moreover, **every offender who is imprisoned for some length of time will likely lose his employment altogether. That plainly cannot be a reason for not meting out a sentence of imprisonment.** This is true also of the potential losses of pensions, bonuses or prospects of promotion. On top of all this, if this was a factor that could be taken into account, it would unfairly work to the detriment of the unemployed, and possibly also those employed on a daily rate, or gig workers and other freelancers.

> Third, the consequences that would arise as a result of the sentence will often be indeterminate at the point when the case is heard before the court.

(emphasis added)

105    Finally, I should state that when calibrating the sentence for the present case, I did not even consider as an aggravating sentencing factor, the utterly shameless and deceitful manner in which the accused had conducted his defence. To say the least, the accused was and continues to be devoid of remorse, capitalising on the fact that the victim was unable to defend himself both at the scene (due to his then personal circumstances), and also in court as he had already passed away. Therefore, the sentence of five weeks’ imprisonment imposed on the accused was more than fair, if not lenient.
